data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected True, was False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Modern assertion | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "expected 3, found N" on failure |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(list)` | If you expect exactly one match |

For the "all users are active" check, `Assert.IsTrue` with `.All()` is fine since there's no built-in "assert all match predicate." But if you just need to verify the admin exists:

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
```
